# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bloody-poetry
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bloody-poetry/a-defence-of-poetry] "**A Defence of Poetry**" is an unfinished essay by Percy Bysshe Shelley written in February and March 1821 that the poet put aside and never completed.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-defence-of-poetry] In 1840, the text was published posthumously in *Essays, Letters from Abroad, Translations and Fragments*.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-defence-of-poetry] Its earliest U.S. publication was by Ginn and Company in Boston in 1891.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-defence-of-poetry] Shelley wrote the essay in response to his friend Thomas Love Peacock's article "The Four Ages of Poetry", which had been published in 1820.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-defence-of-poetry] , I mean to set about an answer to it....
[src:bloody-poetry/a-defence-of-poetry] It is very clever, but I think, very false.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-defence-of-poetry] Your anathemas against poetry itself excited me to a sacred rage. . . .
[src:bloody-poetry/a-defence-of-poetry] The text we know as *A Defence of Poetry* was eventually published eighteen years after Shelley's death, after being subjected to some editing by John Hunt and Shelley's wife Mary Shelley, in her *Essays, Letters from Abroad, Translations and Fragments*.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-defence-of-poetry] Shelley's aim was to show that poets establish morality and inspire the legal norms in a civil society, thus creating a foundation for the other institutions of a community.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-defence-of-poetry] , [Shelley] attempts to prove that poets are philosophers; that they are the creators and protectors of moral and civil laws; and that if it were not for poets, scientists could not have developed either their theories or their inventions.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-defence-of-poetry] The mores so created are codified into laws.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-defence-of-poetry] The social function or utility of poets is that they create and maintain the norms and mores of a society.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-defence-of-poetry] ...Shelley was mainly concerned to explain the moral (and thus the social) function of poetry.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-defence-of-poetry] In doing so, he produced one of the most penetrating general discussions on poetry that we have.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-defence-of-poetry] Shelley’s argument for poetry is an important text of English Romanticism.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-defence-of-poetry] Shelley's conclusive remark that "Poets are the unacknowledged legislators of the world" suggests his awareness of "the profound ambiguity inherent in linguistic means, which he considers at once as an instrument of intellectual freedom and a vehicle for political and social subjugation".
[src:bloody-poetry/a-dirge] "**A Dirge**" is a poetic dirge composed by Percy Bysshe Shelley.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-dirge] It was published posthumously in 1824 by his wife, Mary Shelley, in the collection *Posthumous Poems*.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-dirge] The text has been set to music by Frank Bridge, Charles Ives, Ottorino Respighi, Roy Ewing Agnew, and Benjamin Britten.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-dirge] The rhyme scheme of the eight lines is ABAB CCCB.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-dirge] The triplet of vain/strain/main in the second half of the poem adds to the sense of the piling up of emotions.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-dirge] It also has the effect of slowing down the poem.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-dirge] The dominant themes of the poem are isolation, loneliness, and death.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-dirge] It is a scene of desolation and despair.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-dirge] The wind moans in a grief that cannot be expressed in words; the rain storm billows in vain; the trees are barren and their branches strain under the unceasing onslaught.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-dirge] A dirge is a song meant to invoke and express the emotions of grief and mourning that are typical of a funeral.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-dirge] Images of nature are used to symbolize the grief he feels, such as the moaning and wild wind, the sullen clouds, the sad storm, the bare woods, the deep caves, and the dreary main.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-dirge] He imbues his natural surroundings with anthropomorphic characteristics and qualities to express his grief.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-dirge] The nouns are modified by adjectives that give them human attributes and traits to express his own emotions of dreariness and sadness.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-dirge] He concludes that the whole world is “wrong” and is grieving.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-dirge] Shelley wrote the poem after the deaths of his friend John Keats and his son William who were buried in a cemetery in Rome.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-dirge] The untimely death of Keats reopened the floodgates of emotion for Shelley, inevitably leading him to reexperience the sadness and pain he felt for the death of his infant son.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-dirge] In the second line, “Grief too sad for song,” Shelley argued that the grief was ineffable, inexpressible in words.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-dirge] The last line, “Wail, for the world’s wrong!”, provides a sense of hope and consolation.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-dirge] Rough wind, that moanest loud Grief too sad for song; Wild wind, when sullen cloud Knells all the night long; Sad storm whose tears are vain, Bare woods, whose branches strain, Deep caves and dreary main,— Wail, for the world's wrong!
[src:bloody-poetry/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] "**A Letter to Lord Ellenborough**" is a pamphlet written in 1812 by Percy Bysshe Shelley in defence of Daniel Isaac Eaton.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] Printed in Barnstaple, the essay is approximately 4,000 words in length.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] Shelley defended freedom of speech and criticized the sentencing of publisher Daniel Isaac Eaton.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] Shelley argued against punishing blasphemous libel maintaining that religious belief is involuntary and that opinions, even if false, should not be prosecuted.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] In the essay, Shelley argues for concepts which were then quite radical, including complete freedom of the press, and a tolerance for all published opinion, even when false.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] The epigraph on the title page is by Tacitus from *The Annals*, Deorum Offensa, Diis curae.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] An offense to the gods is rectified by the gods.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] A speech by the Marquess Wellesley from July 2 in the *Globe* is quoted.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] In the Advertisement, Shelley wrote that he had waited for four months for someone to attack the sentence but when none was forthcoming, he wrote the letter.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] The title arises from the name of the letter's recipient, who directed the jury that convicted Eaton.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] Eaton had been tried and found guilty of "blasphemous libel", for being an atheist.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] At the trial before Edward Law, 1st Baron Ellenborough, the Lord Chief Justice of England, what Mark Sandy of the University of Durham has called a "prejudiced jury" convicted Eaton for printing part three of Thomas Paine's *The Age of Reason*.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] Daniel Eaton was put on trial in May 1812.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] During the trial, in which he was accused of being an atheist, as well as the aforementioned "blasphemous libel." In defending himself, Eaton claimed that his beliefs were not atheistic, but deistic.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] He attempted to argue that scripture was open to the type of critique that Thomas Paine had leveled in *The Age of Reason*.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] Despite the paucity of evidence, on 15 May 1812, the Ellenborough-led jury found Eaton guilty.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] His sentence was severe, including eighteen months in Newgate Prison and a monthly pillorying for the entire term of his sentence.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] The letter was originally printed in 1812 in Barnstaple by W.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] Syle, but because they anticipated prosecution, the edition was mostly destroyed, with only 50 copies delivered to London for private distribution.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] It was published in book form in 1859 in the *Shelley Memorials*.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] It was included in *The Prose Works of Percy Bysshe Shelley*, Volume 1, edited by Harry Buxton Forman in 1880, published by Reeves and Turner in London.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] The letter was republished as *Shelley on Blasphemy: Being His Letter to Lord Ellenborough, Occasioned by the Sentence which He Passed on Mr.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] Eaton* in 1883 in London by the Progressive Publishing Company.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] The letter was republished in *A letter to Lord Ellenborough: Occasioned by the Sentence Which He Passed on Mr.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] Eaton as publisher of the third part of Paine's 'Age of Reason'* in 1894 in London by R.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-philosophical-view-of-reform] Shelley composed *A Philosophical View of Reform* between November, 1819 and 20 May 1820, meant to address political developments in England at that time.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-philosophical-view-of-reform] He advocated non-violence and a moderate response to the repressive measures imposed by the British government.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-philosophical-view-of-reform] One of the events he addressed was the Peterloo Massacre, which occurred on 16 August 1819, in St.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-philosophical-view-of-reform] Peter's Field near Manchester, where a peaceful demonstration seeking parliamentary reform was attacked by militia.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-philosophical-view-of-reform] The bookseller Richard Carlile had been found guilty of blasphemy by a jury in November, 1819 for printing an edition of *The Age of Reason* (1794-6) by Thomas Paine.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-philosophical-view-of-reform] The “Six Acts” had been promulgated in December which placed restrictions on public gatherings and freedom of the press.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-philosophical-view-of-reform] It was during this unstable political period in England in late 1819 when Shelley started writing *A Philosophical View of Reform*.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-philosophical-view-of-reform] 4. abolish tithes, and make all religions, all forms of opinion regarding the origin and government of the universe, equal under the law.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-philosophical-view-of-reform] 5. make justice inexpensive, certain, and speedy, and extend the institution of juries to every possible occasion of jurisprudence.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-philosophical-view-of-reform] Shelley opposed revolution, advocating instead gradual change through non-violence.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-philosophical-view-of-reform] He argued that individual and institutional reform went hand in hand.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-philosophical-view-of-reform] He maintained that poets, writers, and philosophers would stimulate reforms of the social institutions that would benefit everyone in society.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-philosophical-view-of-reform] Shelley informed his publisher Charles Ollier on 19 December 1819 that he sought *A Philosophical View of Reform* "to be an instructive and readable book, appealing from the passions to the reason of men", informing him that he would not finish it "this season".
[src:bloody-poetry/a-philosophical-view-of-reform] On 26 May 1820 he asked Leigh Hunt if he could find a publisher for the work: "Do you know any bookseller who wd publish for me an octavo volume entitled 'A philosophical View of Reform'.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-philosophical-view-of-reform] Mary Shelley had a transcript made of the manuscript with plans to publish the work.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-philosophical-view-of-reform] The political essay remained unpublished, however, until 1920 when it appeared for the first time in print in an edition published by Humphrey Milford, Oxford University Press, with an introduction and appendix by Thomas William Rolleston.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] It is a foundational essay advocating for vegetarianism, maintaining that a plant-based diet is essential for bodily health, moral virtue, and social justice.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley argued that meat consumption is unnatural, a "slow but certain poison", causing disease, which "pollutes" the body, and leads to vice and depravity.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] He prescribes the return to a "natural" vegetable diet.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] This work is regarded as one of the earliest and most fervent defenses of vegetarianism in English literature.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley wrote four essays on the subject of vegetarianism, "A Vindication of Natural Diet" (1813), the note in *Queen Mab*, in a section of "A Refutation of Deism" (1814), and "On the Vegetable System of Diet", which was published posthumously in 1929.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley first experimented with a vegetarian diet while at the University of Oxford according to Thomas Jefferson Hogg.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley began a vegetarian diet on 1 March 1812 along with his first wife Harriet Westbrook.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley began composing the essay in October–November 1812.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley met John Frank Newton during 1812-1813 and influenced his views on vegetarianism.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Historian Keith Thomas has noted that Newton's *Return to Nature* "provided much of the basis" for Shelley's *A Vindication of Natural Diet*.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The work has been republished since 1813, beginning with an abridged version which was published in Boston by March, Capen, and Lyon in an American collection *Vegetable Diet: As Sanctioned by Medical Men, and by Experience in All Ages*, edited by William A.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The essay was reprinted in 1884 in a new edition in London by Frederick Pitman and by John Heywood and the Vegetarian Society in Manchester.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The original title page was reproduced: *A Vindication of Natural Diet.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Being One in a Series of Notes to Queen Mab (A Philosophical Poem).* London: Printed for J.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The new edition featured a preface by Henry Stephens Salt and William Axon.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] In 1904, the work was republished in London by C.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Daniel as *A Vindication of Natural Diet and Extracts from the Works of Dr.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley used the imagery of slaughtering a lamb.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] In the novel *Frankenstein; or, The Modern Prometheus* (1818), which he is acknowledged to have contributed to, the Being is portrayed as a vegetarian.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The Being explained his vegetarian diet to Victor Frankenstein: "My food is not that of man.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] I do not destroy the lamb and the kid to glut my appetite; acorns and berries afford me sufficient nourishment." Shelley's views on vegetarianism are routinely incorrectly attributed to his wife.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] In *Laon and Cythna*, republished as *The Revolt of Islam* (1817), Fifth Canto, the Festival of nations held after the Revolution is a banquet where no meat is served.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The feast is vegetarian: "Never again may blood of bird or beast/ Stain with its venomous stream a human feast".
[src:bloody-poetry/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] This is "The banquet of the free" where the guests are described as "reclining as they ate, of Liberty,/ And Hope, and Justice".
[src:bloody-poetry/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The festival was not polluted by gore, "But piled on high, an overflowing store/ Of pomegranates, and citrons, fairest fruit,/ Melons, and dates, and figs, and many a root".
[src:bloody-poetry/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley argued that eating meat was unnatural.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] He maintained that diseases and immorality arose from mankind's "unnatural habits of life".
[src:bloody-poetry/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] A meatless diet was the best regimen for maintaining a healthy and disease-free lifestyle.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] He wrote that human diseases could be decreased by a return to a natural vegetable diet.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley argued that eating meat was a practice that polluted the body with syphilis and resulted in other ailments.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] In *A Vindication of Natural Diet* he wrote, "Should ever a physician be born with the genius of Locke, I am persuaded that he might trace all bodily and mental derangements to our unnatural habits," these unnatural habits being the consumption of meat.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] He cited the allegory of Prometheus who stole fire from the gods which enabled mankind to cook meat, thereby screening the disgust and horror of dead flesh.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] He concluded that a person with compassion and empathy for animals, "rising from a meal of roots", would be able to maintain a healthy and balanced diet and lifestyle.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley presented examples of how a vegetarian diet resulted in longevity and an increased lifespan.
[src:bloody-poetry/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The only threat of death will be that of natural, old age, that "old age would be our last and our only malady".
[src:bloody-poetry/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The two rules he prescribes for a natural diet are to never eat anything that was alive and to drink only distilled water.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Lovelace was the only legitimate child of poet Lord Byron and reformer Anne Isabella Milbanke.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Lord Byron separated from his wife a month after Ada was born, and died when she was eight.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Although often ill in childhood, Lovelace pursued her studies assiduously.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] King was a Baron, and was created Viscount Ockham and 1st Earl of Lovelace in 1838.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] The name Lovelace was chosen because Ada was descended from the extinct Baron Lovelaces.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] The title given to her husband thus made Ada the Countess of Lovelace.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Lovelace's educational and social exploits brought her into contact with scientists such as Andrew Crosse, Charles Babbage, David Brewster, Charles Wheatstone and Michael Faraday, and the author Charles Dickens, contacts which she used to further her education.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Lovelace described her approach as "poetical science" and herself as an "Analyst (& Metaphysician)".
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] When she was eighteen, Lovelace's mathematical talents led her to a long working relationship and friendship with fellow British mathematician Charles Babbage.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] She was particularly interested in Babbage's work on the analytical engine.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Lovelace first met him on 5 June 1833, when she and her mother attended one of Charles Babbage's Saturday night soirées with their mutual friend, and Lovelace's private tutor, Mary Somerville.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Though Babbage's analytical engine was never constructed and did not influence the invention of electronic computers, it has been recognised as a Turing-complete general-purpose computer, which anticipated the essential features of a modern electronic computer.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Babbage is therefore known as the "father of computers," and Lovelace is credited with several computing "firsts" for her collaboration with him.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Lovelace translated an article by the military engineer Luigi Menabrea about the analytical engine, supplementing it with seven long explanatory notes.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] These described a method of using the machine to calculate Bernoulli numbers which is often called the first published computer program.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] She developed a vision of the capability of computers to go beyond mere calculating or number-crunching, while many others, including Babbage, focused only on those capabilities.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Lovelace was the first to point out the possibility of encoding information besides mere arithmetical figures, such as music, and manipulating it with such a machine.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Her mindset of "poetical science" led her to ask questions about the analytical engine, examining how individuals and society relate to technology as a collaborative tool.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Ada is widely commemorated, including in the names of a programming language, roads, buildings and institutes, as well as programmes, lectures and courses.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] There are plaques, statues, paintings, literary and non-fiction works about her.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Lord Byron expected his child to be a "glorious boy" and was disappointed when Lady Byron gave birth to a girl.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] The child was named after Byron's half-sister, Augusta Leigh, and was called "Ada" by Byron himself.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] On 16 January 1816, at Lord Byron's command, Lady Byron left for her parents' home at Kirkby Mallory, taking their five-week-old daughter with her.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Although English law at the time granted full custody of children to the father in cases of separation, Lord Byron made no attempt to claim his parental rights, but did request that his sister keep him informed of Ada's welfare.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] On 21 April, Lord Byron signed the deed of separation, although very reluctantly, and left England for good a few days later.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Aside from an acrimonious separation, Lady Byron continued throughout her life to make allegations about her husband's immoral behaviour.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] This set of events made Lovelace infamous in Victorian society.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Ada did not have a relationship with her father.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] He died in April 1824 when she was eight years old.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Her mother was the only significant parental figure in her life.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Lovelace was not shown the family portrait of her father until her 20th birthday.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Lovelace did not have a close relationship with her mother.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] She was often left in the care of her maternal grandmother Judith, Hon.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] However, because of societal attitudes of the time—which favoured the husband in any separation, with the welfare of any child acting as mitigation—Lady Byron had to present herself as a loving mother to the rest of society.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] This included writing anxious letters to Lady Milbanke about her daughter's welfare, with a cover note saying to retain the letters in case she had to use them to show maternal concern.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] In one letter to Lady Milbanke, she referred to her daughter as "it": "I talk to it for your satisfaction, not my own, and shall be very glad when you have it under your own." Lady Byron had her teenage daughter watched by close friends for any sign of moral deviation.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Lovelace dubbed these observers the "Furies" and later complained they exaggerated and invented stories about her.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Lovelace was often ill, beginning in early childhood.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] At the age of eight, she experienced headaches that obscured her vision.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] In June 1829, she was paralyzed after a bout of measles.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] She was subjected to continuous bed rest for nearly a year, something which may have extended her period of disability.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] By 1831, she was able to walk with crutches.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Despite the illnesses, she developed her mathematical and technological skills.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Ada Byron had an affair with a tutor in early 1833.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] She tried to elope with him after she was caught, but the tutor's relatives recognised her and contacted her mother.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Lady Byron and her friends covered the incident up to prevent a public scandal.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Lovelace never met her younger half-sister, Allegra, the daughter of Lord Byron and Claire Clairmont.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Allegra died in 1822 at the age of five.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Lovelace did have some contact with Elizabeth Medora Leigh, the daughter of Byron's half-sister Augusta Leigh, who purposely avoided Lovelace as much as possible when introduced at court.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Lovelace became close friends with her tutor Mary Somerville, who introduced her to Charles Babbage in 1833.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] She had a strong respect and affection for Somerville, and they corresponded for many years.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Other acquaintances included the scientists Andrew Crosse, Sir David Brewster, Charles Wheatstone, Michael Faraday and the author Charles Dickens.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] She was presented at Court at the age of seventeen "and became a popular belle of the season" in part because of her "brilliant mind".
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] By 1834 Ada was a regular at Court and started attending various events.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] She danced often and was able to charm many people, and was described by most people as being dainty, although John Hobhouse, Byron's friend, described her as "a large, coarse-skinned young woman but with something of my friend's features, particularly the mouth".
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] This description followed their meeting on 24 February 1834 in which Ada made it clear to Hobhouse that she did not like him, probably due to her mother's influence, which led her to dislike all of her father's friends.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] This first impression was not to last, and they later became friends.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] On 8 July 1835, she married William, 8th Baron King, becoming Lady King.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] They had three homes: Ockham Park, Surrey; a Scottish estate on Loch Torridon in Ross-shire; and a house in London.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] They spent their honeymoon at Ashley Combe near Porlock Weir, Somerset, which had been built as a hunting lodge in 1799 and was improved by King in preparation for their honeymoon.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] It later became their summer retreat and was further improved during this time.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] From 1845, the family's main house was Horsley Towers, built in the Tudorbethan fashion by the architect of the Houses of Parliament, Charles Barry, and later greatly enlarged to Lovelace's own designs.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] They had three children: Byron (born 1836); Anne Isabella (called Annabella, born 1837); and Ralph Gordon (born 1839).
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Immediately after the birth of Annabella, Lady King experienced "a tedious and suffering illness, which took months to cure".
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Ada was a descendant of the extinct Barons Lovelace and in 1838, her husband was made Earl of Lovelace and Viscount Ockham, meaning Ada became the Countess of Lovelace.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] In 1843–44, Ada's mother assigned William Benjamin Carpenter to teach Ada's children and to act as a "moral" instructor for Ada.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] He quickly fell for her and encouraged her to express any frustrated affections, claiming that his marriage meant he would never act in an "unbecoming" manner.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] When it became clear that Carpenter was trying to start an affair, Ada cut it off.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] In 1841, Lovelace and Medora Leigh (the daughter of Lord Byron's half-sister Augusta Leigh) were told by Ada's mother that Ada's father was also Medora's father.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] On 27 February 1841, Ada wrote to her mother: "I am not in the least *astonished*.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] She apparently lost more than £3,000 on the horses during the later 1840s.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] The gambling led to her forming a syndicate with male friends, and an ambitious attempt in 1851 to create a mathematical model for successful large bets.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] This went disastrously wrong, leaving her thousands of pounds in debt to the syndicate, forcing her to admit it all to her husband.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] She had a shadowy relationship with Andrew Crosse's son John from 1844 onwards.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] John Crosse destroyed most of their correspondence after her death as part of a legal agreement.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] She bequeathed him the only heirlooms her father had personally left to her.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] During her final illness, she would panic at the idea of the younger Crosse being kept from visiting her.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] From 1832, when she was seventeen, her mathematical abilities began to emerge, and her interest in mathematics dominated the majority of her adult life.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Her mother's obsession with rooting out any of the insanity of which she accused Byron was one of the reasons that Ada was taught mathematics from an early age.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] She was privately educated in mathematics and science by William Frend, William King, and Mary Somerville, the noted 19th-century researcher and scientific author.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] In the 1840s, the mathematician Augustus De Morgan extended her "much help in her mathematical studies" including study of advanced calculus topics including the "numbers of Bernoulli" (that formed her celebrated algorithm for Babbage's Analytical Engine).
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] In a letter to Lady Byron, De Morgan suggested that Ada's skill in mathematics might lead her to become "an original mathematical investigator, perhaps of first-rate eminence".
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Lovelace often questioned basic assumptions through integrating poetry and science.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Lovelace believed that intuition and imagination were critical to effectively applying mathematical and scientific concepts.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] She valued metaphysics as much as mathematics, viewing both as tools for exploring "the unseen worlds around us".
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Lovelace died at the age of 36 on 27 November 1852 from cervical cancer (which contemporary accounts called uterine cancer, since a distinction between the two was not made at that time).
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] The illness lasted several months, in which time Lady Byron took command over whom Ada saw, and excluded all of her friends and confidants.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Under her mother's influence, Ada had a religious transformation and was coaxed into repenting of her previous conduct and making Lady Byron her executor.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] She lost contact with her husband after confessing something to him on 30 August which caused him to abandon her bedside.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] She was buried, at her request, next to her father at the Church of St.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Mary Magdalene in Hucknall, Nottinghamshire.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Throughout her life, Lovelace was strongly interested in scientific developments and fads of the day, including phrenology and mesmerism.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] After her work with Babbage, Lovelace continued to work on other projects.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] In 1844, she commented to a friend Woronzow Greig about her desire to create a mathematical model for how the brain gives rise to thoughts and nerves to feelings ("a calculus of the nervous system").
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] In part, her interest in the brain came from a long-running preoccupation, inherited from her mother, about her "potential" madness.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] As part of her research into this project, she visited the electrical engineer Andrew Crosse in 1844 to learn how to carry out electrical experiments.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] In the same year, she wrote a review of a paper by Baron Karl von Reichenbach, *Researches on Magnetism*, but this was not published and does not appear to have progressed past the first draft.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] In 1851, the year before her cancer struck, she wrote to her mother mentioning "certain productions" she was working on regarding the relation of maths and music.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Lovelace first met Charles Babbage in June 1833, through their mutual friend Mary Somerville.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Later that month, Babbage invited Lovelace to see the prototype for his difference engine.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] She became fascinated with the machine and used her relationship with Somerville to visit Babbage as often as she could.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Babbage was impressed by Lovelace's intellect and analytic skills.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] He called her "The Enchantress of Number".
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] In 1840, Babbage was invited to give a seminar at the University of Turin about his Analytical Engine.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Luigi Menabrea, a young Italian engineer and the future Prime Minister of Italy, transcribed Babbage's lecture into French, and this transcript was subsequently published in the *Bibliothèque universelle de Genève* in October 1842.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Babbage's friend Charles Wheatstone commissioned Lovelace to translate Menabrea's paper into English.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] During a nine-month period in 1842–43, Lovelace translated Menabrea's article.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] She augmented the paper with seven notes, A to G, about three times longer than the translation.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] The translation and notes were then published in the September 1843 edition of Taylor's *Scientific Memoirs* under her initials *AAL*.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Explaining the Analytical Engine's function was a difficult task; many other scientists did not grasp the concept and the British establishment had shown little interest in it.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Lovelace's notes even had to explain how the Analytical Engine differed from the original Difference Engine.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Her work was well received at the time; the scientist Michael Faraday described himself as a supporter of her writing.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Lovelace and Babbage had a minor falling out when the papers were published, when he tried to leave his own statement (criticising the government's treatment of his Engine) as an unsigned preface, which could have been mistakenly interpreted as a joint declaration.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] When Taylor's *Scientific Memoirs* ruled that the statement should be signed, Babbage wrote to Lovelace asking her to withdraw the paper.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] This was the first that she knew he was leaving it unsigned, and she wrote back refusing to withdraw the paper.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] The historian Benjamin Woolley theorised that "His actions suggested he had so enthusiastically sought Ada's involvement, and so happily indulged her ... because of her 'celebrated name'." Their friendship recovered, and they continued to correspond.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] On 12 August 1851, when she was dying of cancer, Lovelace wrote to him asking him to be her executor, though this letter did not give him the necessary legal authority.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Part of the terrace at Worthy Manor was known as *Philosopher's Walk;* it was there that Lovelace and Babbage were reputed to have walked while discussing mathematical principles.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] The notes are important in the early history of computers, especially since Note G described, in complete detail, a method for calculating a sequence of Bernoulli numbers using the Analytical Engine, which might have run correctly had it ever been built.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Though Babbage's personal notes from 1837 to 1840 contain the first programs for the engine, the algorithm in Note G is often called the first published computer program.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] The engine was never completed and so the program was never tested.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] In 1953, more than a century after her death, Ada Lovelace's notes on Babbage's Analytical Engine were republished as an appendix to B.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Bowden's *Faster than Thought: A Symposium on Digital Computing Machines*.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] The engine has now been recognised as an early model for a computer and her notes as a description of a computer and software.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Based on this work, Lovelace is often called the first computer programmer and her method has been called the world's first computer program.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Eugene Eric Kim and Lovelace biographer, Betty Alexandra Toole, argued it was "incorrect" to regard Lovelace as the first computer programmer in an article for Scientific American.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Bromley notes several dozen sample programs prepared by Babbage between 1837 and 1840, all substantially predating Lovelace's notes.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Stein regards Lovelace's notes as "more a reflection of the mathematical uncertainty of the author, the political purposes of the inventor, and, above all, of the social and cultural context in which it was written, than a blueprint for a scientific development".
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Bruce Collier wrote that Lovelace "made a considerable contribution to publicizing the Analytical Engine, but there is no evidence that she advanced the design or theory of it in any way".
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Doron Swade has said that Ada only published the first computer program instead of actually writing it, but agrees that she was the only person to see the potential of the analytical engine as a machine capable of expressing entities other than quantities.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] In his book, *Idea Makers*, Stephen Wolfram defends Lovelace's contributions.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] While acknowledging that Babbage wrote several unpublished algorithms for the Analytical Engine prior to Lovelace's notes, Wolfram argues that "there's nothing as sophisticated—or as clean—as Ada's computation of the Bernoulli numbers.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Babbage certainly helped and commented on Ada's work, but she was definitely the driver of it." Wolfram then suggests that Lovelace's main achievement was to distill from Babbage's correspondence "a clear exposition of the abstract operation of the machine—something which Babbage never did".
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] In her notes, Ada Lovelace emphasised the difference between the Analytical Engine and previous calculating machines, particularly its ability to be programmed to solve problems of any complexity.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] She realised the potential of the device extended far beyond mere number crunching.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] This analysis was an important development from previous ideas about the capabilities of computing devices and anticipated the implications of modern computing one hundred years before they were realised.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] This objection has been the subject of much debate and rebuttal, including in the paper that originally coined it.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Lovelace recognized the difference between the details of the computing mechanism, as covered in an 1834 article on the Difference Engine, and the logical structure of the Analytical Engine, on which the article she was reviewing dwelt.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] She noted that different specialists might be required in each area.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] The computer language Ada, created on behalf of the United States Department of Defense, was named after Lovelace.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] The reference manual for the language was approved on 10 December 1980 and the Department of Defense Military Standard for the language, *MIL-STD-1815*, was given the number of the year of her birth.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] In 1981, the Association for Women in Computing inaugurated its Ada Lovelace Award.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] As of 1998, the British Computer Society (BCS) has awarded the Lovelace Medal, and in 2008 initiated an annual competition for women students.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] BCSWomen sponsors the Lovelace Colloquium, an annual conference for women undergraduates.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] In 2013, the University of Deusto in Spain established the Ada Byron Award for women in technology, which was subsequently expanded to several Latin American countries.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Ada, the National College for Digital Skills, is a specialist college of further education and higher education in England, focused on digital skills.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] The college has campuses in London (Pimlico) and Manchester (Ancoats).
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] The college teaches degree-level apprenticeship, as well as a sixth-form college for students aged 16 to 19.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Ada Lovelace Day is an annual event celebrated on the second Tuesday of October, which began in 2009.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Its goal is to "... raise the profile of women in science, technology, engineering, and maths," and to "create new role models for girls and women" in these fields.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Events have included Wikipedia edit-a-thons with the aim of improving the representation of women on Wikipedia in terms of articles and editors to reduce unintended gender bias on Wikipedia.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] The Ada Initiative was a non-profit organisation dedicated to increasing the involvement of women in the free culture and open source movements.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] The building of the department of Engineering Mathematics at the University of Bristol is called the Ada Lovelace Building.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] The Engineering in Computer Science and Telecommunications College building in Zaragoza University is called the Ada Byron Building.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] The computer centre in the village of Porlock, near where Lovelace lived, is named after her.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Ada Lovelace House is a council-owned building in Kirkby-in-Ashfield, Nottinghamshire, near where Lovelace spent her infancy.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] In 2012, a Google Doodle and blog post honoured her on her birthday.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] In 2013, Ada Developers Academy was founded and named after her.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Its mission is to diversify tech by providing women and gender-diverse people the skills, experience, and community support to become professional software developers to change the face of tech.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] On 17 September 2013, the BBC Radio 4 biography programme *Great Lives* devoted an episode to Ada Lovelace; she was sponsored by TV presenter Konnie Huq.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] As of November 2015, all new British passports have included an illustration of Lovelace and Babbage.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] In 2017, a Google Doodle honoured her with other women on International Women's Day.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] On 2 February 2018, Satellogic, a high-resolution Earth observation imaging and analytics company, launched a ÑuSat type micro-satellite named in honour of Ada Lovelace.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] In March 2018, *The New York Times* published a belated obituary for Ada Lovelace.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] On 27 July 2018, Senator Ron Wyden submitted, in the United States Senate, the designation of 9 October 2018 as National Ada Lovelace Day: "To honor the life and contributions of Ada Lovelace as a leading woman in science and mathematics".
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] The resolution (S.Res.592) was considered, and agreed to without amendment and with a preamble by unanimous consent.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] In November 2020 it was announced that Trinity College Dublin, whose library had previously held forty busts, all of them of men, was commissioning four new busts of women, one of whom was to be Lovelace.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] In March 2022, a statue of Ada Lovelace was installed at the site of the former Ergon House in the City of Westminster, London, honouring its scientific history.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] The redevelopment was part of a complex with Imperial Chemical House.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] The statue was sculpted by Etienne and Mary Millner and based on the portrait by Margaret Sarah Carpenter.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] The sculpture was unveiled on International Women's Day, 2022.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] It stands on the 7th floor of Millbank Quarter overlooking the junction of Dean Bradley Street and Horseferry Road.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] The 2022 graphics processor microarchitecture from Nvidia is named Ada Lovelace.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] In 2025, the National Portrait Gallery acquired three images of Lovelace–the only known photographs of Lovelace.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Two were daguerreotypes by Antoine Claudet and were taken around 1843.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] The third was by an unknown photographer and is of Henry Wyndham Phillips’ portrait of Lovelace.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] In February 2026, a statue of Lovelace was unveiled on the Hinckley campus of the North Warwickshire and South Leicestershire College.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Special exhibitions were displayed by the Science Museum in London, England and the Weston Library (part of the Bodleian Library) in Oxford, England.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Lovelace is portrayed in Romulus Linney's 1977 play *Childe Byron*.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] In Tom Stoppard's 1993 play *Arcadia*, the precocious teenage genius Thomasina Coverly—a character "apparently based" on Ada Lovelace (the play also involves Lord Byron)—comes to understand chaos theory, and theorises the second law of thermodynamics, before either is officially recognised.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] In the 1990 steampunk novel *The Difference Engine* by William Gibson and Bruce Sterling, Lovelace delivers a lecture on the "punched cards" programme which proves Gödel's incompleteness theorems decades before their actual discovery.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Lovelace and Mary Shelley as teenagers are the central characters in Jordan Stratford's steampunk series, *The Wollstonecraft Detective Agency*.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Lovelace features in John Crowley's 2005 novel, *Lord Byron's Novel: The Evening Land*, as an unseen character whose personality is forcefully depicted in her annotations and anti-heroic efforts to archive her father's lost novel.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] The 2015 play *Ada and the Engine* by Lauren Gunderson portrays Lovelace and Charles Babbage in unrequited love, and it imagines a post-death meeting between Lovelace and her father.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Lovelace and Babbage are also the main characters in Sydney Padua's webcomic and graphic novel *The Thrilling Adventures of Lovelace and Babbage*.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] The comic features extensive footnotes on the history of Ada Lovelace, and many lines of dialogue are drawn from actual correspondence.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Poet Jessy Randall included a tribute to Lovelace in her 2025 collection of poems about women scientists, *The Path of Most Resistance*.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] In the 1997 film *Conceiving Ada*, a computer scientist obsessed with Ada finds a way of communicating with her in the past by means of "undying information waves".
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Lovelace, identified as Ada Augusta Byron, is portrayed by Lily Lesser in the second series of *The Frankenstein Chronicles* aired on ITV in 2017.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] She is employed as an "analyst" to provide the workings of a life-sized humanoid automaton.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] The brass workings of the machine are reminiscent of Babbage's analytical engine.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Her employment is described as keeping her occupied until she returns to her studies in advanced mathematics.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] "Lovelace" is the name of the operating system designed by the character Cameron Howe in *Halt and Catch Fire*, which aired on AMC in the US in 2015.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] In the documentary *Calculating Ada: The Countess of Computing* (2015), Dr Hannah Fry covers the life of Ada Lovelace.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Lovelace and Babbage appear as characters in the second season of the ITV series *Victoria* (2017).
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Lovelace features as a character in "Spyfall, Part 2", the second episode of *Doctor Who*, series 12, which first aired on BBC One on 5 January 2020.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] The character was portrayed by Sylvie Briggs, alongside characterisations of Charles Babbage and Noor Inayat Khan.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Six copies of the 1843 first edition of *Sketch of the Analytical Engine* with Ada Lovelace's "Notes" have been located.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] Three are held at Harvard University, one at the University of Oklahoma, and one at the United States Air Force Academy.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] On 20 July 2018, the sixth copy was sold at auction to an anonymous buyer for £95,000.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] A digital facsimile of one of the copies in the Harvard University Library is available online.
[src:bloody-poetry/ada-lovelace] In December 2016, a letter written by Ada Lovelace was forfeited by Martin Shkreli to the New York State Department of Taxation and Finance for unpaid taxes owed by Shkreli.
[src:bloody-poetry/bloody-poetry] The play had its roots in Brenton's involvement with the small touring company Foco Novo and was the third, and final, show he wrote for them.
[src:bloody-poetry/bloody-poetry] In his introduction to the play Brenton disclaims any interest in moralising over the actions of his characters, as he had in a programme to his earlier play *Weapons of Happiness*.
[src:bloody-poetry/bloody-poetry] Nightingale Theatre produced the play in the summer of 1994 at The Union Chapel, Islington, London.
[src:bloody-poetry/bloody-poetry] Kate Godfrey (Claire Clairmont), Jane Gooderham (Harriet Westbrook), Melee Hutton (Mary Shelley), Mark Norton (Percy Bysshe Shelley), Peter Quilter (George Byron). with Cordelia Monsey directing.
[src:bloody-poetry/bloody-poetry] The play played at the Manhattan Theatre Club in 1987 in a production directed by Lynne Meadow and was revived in 1988 at the Royal Court Theatre and in 2007 at the Chapter Arts Centre, Cardiff.
[src:bloody-poetry/bloody-poetry] The play was staged by emerging company Invulnerable Nothings at The Brooklyn Art Library in 2016.
